Klotz answers Niebuhr, who charges the Declamator with saying that these three men were condemned to exile by the Co· mitia Centuriata; and he correctly main- tains that this is not said here, but it is said that the men were condemned for something, and avoided the punishment by going into exile, as they could do. Niebuhr also says that ‘ exilium ' was never inflicted as a punishment before the enact- ment of the Lex Calpurnia de Ambitu3 but ‘exilium ' was no part of the penalty of the Lex Calpurnia. Niebuhr also thinks that the story of Ahala being recalled may be as destitute of foundation as that of Kaeso. To this Klotz replies that it is not said here that they were recalled by the people in the Comitia Centuriata, but ‘⁴ he only states that they were restored to their former dig- nity by the people, who were afterwards reconciled to them.'’ Let it be so.
